## Author('Adam Spiegler')
## Institution('Loyola University Chicago')

DOCUMENT();       

loadMacros("PG.pl",
           "PGbasicmacros.pl",
           "PGchoicemacros.pl",
           "PGanswermacros.pl",
           "PGgraphmacros.pl",
           "PGauxiliaryFunctions.pl",
           "PGgraphmacros.pl"
           );
       
TEXT(beginproblem()); # standard preamble to each problem.


$showPartialCorrectAnswers = 1;

$dx = random(2,4,1);
$x[0]=0;
$x[1]=0+$dx;
$x[2]=$x[1]+$dx;

$v[0] = random(1500,2500,100);
$m = random(30,100,10);
$dv = $m*$dx;
for ($i = 1; $i<=2; $i++){$v[$i]=$v[$i-1]-$dv};
$ans = "$v[0] - $m t";

BEGIN_TEXT
Question 24:
$BR $SPACE $BR
Find a formula for the linear function whose data is given in the table below.
$BR $SPACE $BR
\{ begintable(4) \}
\{ row("Year, t", @x ) \}
\{ row("Value of a computer, V", @v ) \}
\{ endtable \}
$BR $SPACE $BR
\( V(t) = \ \) \{ ans_rule(20) \}
END_TEXT

ANS(fun_cmp($ans,vars=>'t'));

SOLUTION(EV3(<<'END_SOLUTION'));
$BR $SPACE $BR
$BBOLD SOLUTION $EBOLD
$BR
We have a $BITALIC V${EITALIC}-intercept of $v[0].  Since the value is decreasing by ${DOLLAR}$dv for every $dx years, the slope is 
$BR $SPACE $BR
\( m = \frac{ \triangle V}{\triangle t} = \frac{-$dv}{$dx} = -$m \)
$BR $SPACE $BR
So one possible way to write this equation is
$BR $SPACE $BR
\( V(t) = $v[0] - $m t \)
$BR
END_SOLUTION
     
ENDDOCUMENT();   # This should be the last executable line in the problem.